[Event "Semmering"]
[Site "Semmering"]
[Date "1926.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Janowski, Dawid Markelowicz"]
[Black "Michel, Walter"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "D00"]
[Annotator "McGrew 2015"]
[PlyCount "29"]
[EventDate "1926.??.??"]
[Source "ChessBase"]
[SourceDate "1999.07.01"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 {Wait, this isn't a Stonewall! Patience -- in a few more
moves, the classic pawn structure will appear on the board ...} 2... d5 3. e3
e6 4. Bd3 c5 5. c3 Nbd7 6. f4 {That is more like it -- the only difference, of
course, is that White's Bishop is outside of the wall. In this case, that
gives Black one extra idea, since White's b-pawn is weaker than it would
normally be.} 6... Qb6 {Black promptly probes at the weak point.} 7. Qc2 {
Janowski puts his Queen on her most natural square. There is, however, a
drawback to this: Black can push away White's Bishop and then jump into e4.} (
7. Qc1 {would enable White to meet} 7... c4 {with} 8. Bc2 {
keeping an eye on the e4 square. Then White could meet} 8... Ng4 {with} 9. b3 {
when the position is difficult for both sides.}) (7. b3 {is another way of
meeting Black's blunt attack. White sometimes worries about moves like this
because later White's lack of control of squares on the c-file -- particularly
c3 -- may give Black some extra options. But at the moment it is not clear how
Black can exploit that small weakening of the pawn structure.}) 7... c4 {
Very logical: Black plays to dominate the e4 square.} 8. Be2 Ne4 9. Bh4 {
Preserving the Bishop and keeping both the d-pawn and the f-pawn focused on e5.
} 9... f5 {Black opts for a Double Stonewall, perhaps reasoning that as he was
the first to occupy the central strong point, this should favor him. However,
the fact that White has his "bad" Bishop out whereas Black's is still buried
on c8 is a factor that counts on the other side.} (9... Bd6 10. Nd2 Ndf6 11.
Bxf6 Nxf6 {looks better, when Black has approximate equality despite his
locked-in Bishop. White's weak e-pawn gives Black some mini-threats, e.g.} 12.
Ngf3 Ng4 {when White must resort to the undeveloping move} 13. Nf1 {
It is hard to believe that Black stands any worse here.}) 10. Nf3 Qa5 11. Ne5
b5 $2 {Black is blind to what is happening on the other side of the board.} 12.
Nd2 $2 {And White also misses a first opportunity here!} (12. Bh5+ $1 {
wins on the spot. I suspect that Janowski did not see how White can get his
Knight back out of the cornerafter} 12... g6 13. Nxg6 Ndf6 14. Bxf6 Nxf6 15.
Nxh8+ Nxh5 {However, White has a nice tactical resource in} 16. g4 $1 Nf6 (
16... fxg4 $4 17. Qxh7 {is immediately fatal.}) 17. g5 $1 Nd7 ({Or} 17... Ng4
18. h3 $1 Nxe3 19. Qe2 $1 $18 {trapping Black's Knight.}) 18. Qe2 $18 {
and White's Queen comes in at h5, after which the Knight swings back out of
the corner at f7.}) 12... Nxd2 13. Bh5+ $1 {There we go!} 13... g6 14. Nxg6 Nb6
{Falling on his sword.} 15. Ne5# 1-0

