1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Ne5 e6 4. Bg5 {
Another case of a Stonewall with the Bishop outside the pawn chain.} 4... Be7
5. e3 c5 6. c3 O-O 7. Nd2 b6 {It is tempting to find a place for the
lightsquare Bishop like this, but the pawn on b6 takes away the possibility of
...Qb6. Black never gets any counterplay against White's queenside pawns, and
that means that White has a free hand to pursue the attack on the other wing.}
8. f4 Bb7 $6 ({The only logical follow-up I can see to Black's ...b6 is to
trade off White's good Bishop with} 8... Ba6) 9. Qc2 Nbd7 10. Be2 (10. Bd3 {
would invite} 10... c4 {-- though I am not sure Black should want to lock up
the position like that, removing all of his central pressure on White's pawn
structure.}) 10... h6 11. h4 $5 {This kind of "passive" sacrifice, leaving the
attacked piece to be taken on this square, is well known in such positions.
Usually, however, White's Queen is ready to come to h6 in a single bound --
and that spells doom for Black. Here, matters are more complex.} 11... hxg5 12.
hxg5 Ne4 {
The only possible move. Black keeps the diagonal from c2 to h7 blockaded.} 13.
Nxe4 dxe4 14. O-O-O Nxe5 $2 {This move leaves Black without any chances at all.
} (14... cxd4 {looks at first blush like a winning defensive try. But White
has a truly insane response -- clear everything out of the way in the service
of getting the Queen to f2, from which she can hop to g4 to deliver mate.} 15.
Ba6 $3 Bxa6 (15... d3 16. Qf2 Nxe5 17. Bxb7 d2+ 18. Rxd2 Nd3+ 19. Rxd3 Qxd3 20.
Qh4 Qxe3+ 21. Kb1 Qd3+ 22. Ka1 f5 23. Qh5 $18) 16. Nc6 $1 (16. Qf2 {
doesn't work yet because of} 16... Nxe5 17. Qh4 f5 $19) 16... Qe8 17. Qf2 {
Now Black doesn't have a Knight to take on e5.} 17... f5 $3 {
Only this move holds the position.} (17... f6 18. g6 $3 {
wins since Black cannot take the pawn.} 18... f5 19. Qg3 Nf6 20. Nxe7+ $1 Qxe7
21. Qh4 {and White mates on h8 in a few moves.}) 18. Qh4 (18. g6 {
doesn't actually threaten mate since White's Queen cannot use the h4 square.})
18... Be2 $1 19. Rxd4 Kf7 $1 {Black's position looks precarious, but White has
sacrificed both of his Bishops to get this far, and it appears now that he had
better take equality with} 20. g6+ Kxg6 21. Nxe7+ Kf7 22. Nc6 Nf6 23. Ne5+ Ke7
24. Qg5 $11 {and White will give perpetual check with his Knight at e5 and g6.}
) 15. dxe5 {Hitting the Queen. Now Black's Knight can never come to the aid of
the King, so White can organize his attack with no counterplay to worry about.}
15... Qe8 16. Rh3 f6 17. Bc4 Bd5 18. Rxd5 $1 {The White Bishop is really the
star piece here, so sacrificing the exchange on d5 makes a lot of sense.} 18...
b5 (18... exd5 19. Bxd5+ Rf7 20. g6 $18 {is crushing.}) 19. gxf6 bxc4 20. Qxe4
exd5 21. Qh7+ Kf7 22. Qxg7+ (22. Qxg7+ Ke6 23. Qg4+ $1 {forces the King back
to the kingside, after which White delivers the knockout blow with} 23... Kf7
24. Rh7#) 1-0

