{This game gives a wonderful illustration of White's main attacking plan in
the Stonewall.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. e3 e6 3. Bd3 c5 4. c3 Nc6 (4... b6 5. Nd2 Ba6 $5 {
would be an interesting try here.}) 5. Nd2 {
White takes a grip on e4 before Black can even think of putting a Knight there.
} 5... b6 6. f4 Bb7 7. Ngf3 Bd6 {It looks wrong to put a Bishop on d6 rather
than a pawn. Black really needs a pawn there to keep White's Knight out of e5.}
8. O-O O-O 9. Ne5 Nd5 10. Rf3 {Lifting the Rook up into the attack.} 10... cxd4
$2 {Black may have thought that he had another move to think about the
kingside, but White ignores the center and blasts away on the wing.} 11. Bxh7+
$1 {The standard sacrifice. Black is utterly lost.} 11... Kh8 (11... Kxh7 12.
Rh3+ Kg8 13. Qh5 {is deadly because White's Queen is being assisted by the
Rook, which means that there are two focal points for the mate -- one at h7
and one at h8. Notice how the Knight on e5 keeps an eye on the f7 square,
whether Black has a pawn there or not.} 13... f6 14. Qh8#) 12. Rh3 g5 13. Bd3+
Kg7 14. Qh5 1-0

