1. d4 d5 2. e3 e6 3. c3 c6 4. Bd3 Nf6 5. Nd2 Nbd7 6. f4 c5 7. Ngf3 c4 $2 {
A pointless move -- White's Bishop will be just as strong on c2 as on d3, and
Black will have no pressure on White's center.} 8. Bc2 Be7 9. O-O Nb6 10. Ne5
O-O 11. Rf3 {Now White is set to try one of a number of plans depending on how
Black continues.} 11... g6 {Black decides to try to lock up the kingside,
closing the vital diagonal leading to h7.} (11... Bd7 {is a fairly meaningless
move that lets us see some of White's other plans in action.} 12. Rh3 (12. g4 {
This is another well-known way to proceed, booting Black's Knight out of f6.}
12... Rc8 13. g5 Ne8 (13... Nh5 14. Rh3 g6 15. Rxh5 gxh5 16. Qxh5 f5 17. gxf6
Rxf6 18. Qxh7+ Kf8 19. Qh8#) 14. Bxh7+ Kxh7 15. Rh3+ Kg8 16. Qh5 f6 17. Qh7#)
12... Rc8 $2 13. Bxh7+ $1 Nxh7 14. Qh5 $1 $18 {A pattern worth remembering.})
12. g4 Kg7 13. g5 Ng8 ({He had to try} 13... Nfd7) 14. Rh3 f5 15. Qe1 {
Black is so tangled up -- look at the Knight on g8! -- that he has no decent
defense against White's plan ofQh4xh7#} 15... Nd7 16. Qh4 Nxe5 $4 (16... h6 17.
Ndf3 h5 18. Nxg6 $1 Kxg6 19. Qxh5+ Kg7 20. Qh7#) 17. Qxh7# 1-0

