1. d4 Nf6 2. e3 e6 3. Bd3 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. f4 cxd4 {This is a good example of a
situation where the exchange of pawns is premature. In a few moves, White will
make good use of the open e-file to create some non-standard tactical patterns.
} 6. exd4 Be7 7. Nf3 b6 8. O-O Bb7 9. Nbd2 O-O 10. Ne5 Qc7 11. Qe2 $1 {
This is a very good move. The Queen looks at Black's e-pawn "through" the
Knight on e5.    If that comment makes no sense to you right now, proceed for
a few more moves and all will become clear.} 11... Rfe8 $2 {Black is weakening
his f7 pawn by moving away from its defense like this, but no doubt he had
visions of ...d6 and ...e5 when the Rook would be powerful standing opposite
White's Queen.} 12. Ndf3 d6 13. Nxf7 $1 {Surprise! This sacrificial pattern is
known from other openings, but it is rare in the Stonewall.} 13... Kxf7 14.
Ng5+ $1 Kg8 15. Qxe6+ Kh8 {Now White has a chance to wrap things up with a
pretty combination known as a Smothered Mate.} 16. Nf7+ Kg8 17. Nh6+ Kh8 18.
Qg8+ 1-0

