1. d4 d5 2. e3 Nf6 3. Bd3 e6 4. f4 c5 5. c3 Nc6 6. Nd2 Bd7 7. Ngf3 cxd4 8. exd4
Bd6 9. Ne5 O-O 10. O-O Rb8 {Black begins a positional plan for a minority
attack on the queenside. This is a great strategic idea, but tactically it is
far too slow.} 11. Rf3 {
White doesn't mess around -- it's time to wheel up the heavy artillery!} 11...
b5 12. Rh3 b4 $4 {
Black is fixated on the queenside. That's not where things are happening!} (
12... g6 {was necessary to slow down the attack.}) 13. Bxh7+ $1 {Once White
a Rook on h3, this pattern is often possible. White must just check to make
sure Black cannot defend the Knight where it will stand on h7.} 13... Nxh7 (
13... Kh8 14. Bg6+ Kg8 {
allows a very nice tactical trick based on the position of Black's Queen:} 15.
Bxf7+ $1 Rxf7 16. Rh8+ $1 Kxh8 17. Nxf7+ $18 {etc.}) 14. Qh5 $1 {Now if Black
has his other Knight on d7, he could play ...Ndf6! and stop the attack cold.
But he does not -- so he is getting mated.} 14... Re8 15. Qxf7+ $1 {
Setting up a pretty mate.} (15. Qxf7+ Kh8 16. Ng6#) 1-0

